    {
      "id": "d64b63eefddd48f07e3e0f0e51ed0f28d6f5f75e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-02-22 05:58:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nAgain, what my concern for this patch is that the OBD_ALLOC_LARGE() is called on so many critical paths, the performance might drop silently when the allocate size exceeding the vmalloc threashold. On the other hand, without this patch, the possibility of allocation failure will be higher.\r\n\r\nMy personal opinion is that we should make sure exactly the vmalloc is only be called on non-critical path. If we have to allocate large trunk of memory on critical path, then we must face to the risk of ENOMEM failure on the system which is short of memory.\r\n\r\nOf course, it doesn't mean that I object the OBD_ALLOC_LARGE(), It's fine to me either. :)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a67348826bf462e9552c96ea77fb40682d7b5085",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-02-24 06:01:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, approved\n\nI would really prefer that independent patches (like the OBD_ALLOC_LARGE() patch) be landed separately, even if there are dependencies.\n\nHowever, this patch has gotten many inspections and passed acc-sm in the past, so I don't object to landing it now.  The changes for the ioctl buffer size are a very minor addition to this change.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "226a087d0be119cc1b19989f9ac36042482fe631",
